{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019G1iq1MvKDtMPeefP73wWw","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# data-flow\n2\t\n3\tPurpose: Describes how an HTTP request moves through the userservice composite — from the ServeMux registered in main.go, through the handlers layer, into the store, and back as a JSON response.\n4\t\n5\tTags: data-flow, architecture\n6\t\n7\t## Request Path\n8\t\n9\tEvery request to the user service follows the same linear path: the `ServeMux` in `main.go` dispatches to a `Handler` method in `handlers`, which calls one method on the `Store` interface, and the result is encoded as JSON and written to the response.\n10\t\n11\t```\n12\tHTTP Client\n13\t    |\n14\t    | HTTP request (e.g. POST /users)\n15\t    v\n16\tmain.go — *http.ServeMux\n17\t    |\n18\t    | matched route dispatched to Handler method\n19\t    v\n20\thandlers.Handler  (reads/writes http.ResponseWriter, *http.Request)\n21\t    |\n22\t    | calls Store interface method (Create / Get / Update / Delete)\n23\t    v\n24\tstore.Store  (mutex-guarded map[string]User)\n25\t    |\n26\t    | returns (User, error) or error\n27\t    v\n28\thandlers.Handler  (encodes result as JSON via writeJSON / writeError)\n29\t    |\n30\t    | HTTP response (JSON body, status code)\n31\t    v\n32\tHTTP Client\n33\t```\n34\t\n35\t## Interface Boundary\n36\t\n37\tThe coupling between `handlers` and `store` is intentionally indirect. `handlers` defines a `Store` interface; `store` provides the concrete `*store.Store` type that satisfies it. `main.go` is the only site where the concrete type is referenced — it passes a `*store.Store` to `handlers.New`. This means the two sub-packages are independently testable with no import cycle.\n38\t\n39\t## Concurrency\n40\t\n41\tAll store operations are safe for concurrent use. Read operations (`Get`) hold a shared read lock; write operations (`Create`, `Update`, `Delete`) hold an exclusive write lock. The `handlers` package is stateless between requests and adds no additional synchronisation of its own.\n42\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7d68436b-28de-4036-823d-0ff13e25f918","uuid":"9ad26b2e-8ca4-4dc5-90d7-9cbe1c3bbc07","timestamp":"2026-04-05T22:46:24.784Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/david/Go/src/github.com/cornjacket/ai-builder/establish-regression-recordings/sandbox/regressions/doc-user-service/output/internal/userservice/data-flow.md","content":"# data-flow\n\nPurpose: Describes how an HTTP request moves through the userservice composite — from the ServeMux registered in main.go, through the handlers layer, into the store, and back as a JSON response.\n\nTags: data-flow, architecture\n\n## Request Path\n\nEvery request to the user service follows the same linear path: the `ServeMux` in `main.go` dispatches to a `Handler` method in `handlers`, which calls one method on the `Store` interface, and the result is encoded as JSON and written to the response.\n\n```\nHTTP Client\n    |\n    | HTTP request (e.g. POST /users)\n    v\nmain.go — *http.ServeMux\n    |\n    | matched route dispatched to Handler method\n    v\nhandlers.Handler  (reads/writes http.ResponseWriter, *http.Request)\n    |\n    | calls Store interface method (Create / Get / Update / Delete)\n    v\nstore.Store  (mutex-guarded map[string]User)\n    |\n    | returns (User, error) or error\n    v\nhandlers.Handler  (encodes result as JSON via writeJSON / writeError)\n    |\n    | HTTP response (JSON body, status code)\n    v\nHTTP Client\n```\n\n## Interface Boundary\n\nThe coupling between `handlers` and `store` is intentionally indirect. `handlers` defines a `Store` interface; `store` provides the concrete `*store.Store` type that satisfies it. `main.go` is the only site where the concrete type is referenced — it passes a `*store.Store` to `handlers.New`. This means the two sub-packages are independently testable with no import cycle.\n\n## Concurrency\n\nAll store operations are safe for concurrent use. Read operations (`Get`) hold a shared read lock; write operations (`Create`, `Update`, `Delete`) hold an exclusive write lock. The `handlers` package is stateless between requests and adds no additional synchronisation of its own.\n","numLines":42,"startLine":1,"totalLines":42}}}
