{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DmysX3eTf7LHaGQEX9nnGB","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# data-flow\n2\t\n3\tPurpose: Describes how an inbound HTTP request crosses the internal/ package boundary and is processed by the userservice sub-tree before a response is returned to the caller.\n4\tCovers the entry point in main.go and the handoff into the internal sub-packages.\n5\t\n6\tTags: data-flow, architecture\n7\t\n8\t## Entry into the Internal Boundary\n9\t\n10\tAll execution that uses the `internal/` packages originates in `main.go`. At startup, `main.go` constructs a `*store.Store` and a `handlers.Handler`, registers routes on a `*http.ServeMux`, and begins listening on `:8080`. Once the server is running, the only interaction with the internal packages is inbound HTTP requests dispatched by the mux.\n11\t\n12\t```\n13\tmain.go (project root)\n14\t    |\n15\t    | instantiates store.New() → *store.Store\n16\t    | instantiates handlers.New(*store.Store) → handlers.Handler\n17\t    | registers routes via Handler.RegisterRoutes(*http.ServeMux)\n18\t    |\n19\t    v\n20\t[ internal/ boundary ]\n21\t    |\n22\t    | inbound HTTP request (e.g. PUT /users/{id})\n23\t    v\n24\tuserservice/handlers  — decodes request, calls Store interface method\n25\t    |\n26\t    v\n27\tuserservice/store     — executes mutex-guarded map operation, returns result\n28\t    |\n29\t    v\n30\tuserservice/handlers  — encodes result as JSON, writes HTTP response\n31\t    |\n32\t    v\n33\t[ response exits internal/ boundary → HTTP client ]\n34\t```\n35\t\n36\t## Package Coupling\n37\t\n38\tThe two sub-packages inside `userservice/` are decoupled from each other at the import level. `handlers` defines the `Store` interface it requires; `store` provides the concrete type that satisfies it. Neither package imports the other. Only `main.go`, outside the `internal/` boundary, holds the concrete type reference and performs the wiring. This structure keeps each sub-package independently testable.\n39\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7d68436b-28de-4036-823d-0ff13e25f918","uuid":"ecdca19a-123f-4add-8bc0-77d70e1df41a","timestamp":"2026-04-05T22:46:25.076Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/david/Go/src/github.com/cornjacket/ai-builder/establish-regression-recordings/sandbox/regressions/doc-user-service/output/internal/data-flow.md","content":"# data-flow\n\nPurpose: Describes how an inbound HTTP request crosses the internal/ package boundary and is processed by the userservice sub-tree before a response is returned to the caller.\nCovers the entry point in main.go and the handoff into the internal sub-packages.\n\nTags: data-flow, architecture\n\n## Entry into the Internal Boundary\n\nAll execution that uses the `internal/` packages originates in `main.go`. At startup, `main.go` constructs a `*store.Store` and a `handlers.Handler`, registers routes on a `*http.ServeMux`, and begins listening on `:8080`. Once the server is running, the only interaction with the internal packages is inbound HTTP requests dispatched by the mux.\n\n```\nmain.go (project root)\n    |\n    | instantiates store.New() → *store.Store\n    | instantiates handlers.New(*store.Store) → handlers.Handler\n    | registers routes via Handler.RegisterRoutes(*http.ServeMux)\n    |\n    v\n[ internal/ boundary ]\n    |\n    | inbound HTTP request (e.g. PUT /users/{id})\n    v\nuserservice/handlers  — decodes request, calls Store interface method\n    |\n    v\nuserservice/store     — executes mutex-guarded map operation, returns result\n    |\n    v\nuserservice/handlers  — encodes result as JSON, writes HTTP response\n    |\n    v\n[ response exits internal/ boundary → HTTP client ]\n```\n\n## Package Coupling\n\nThe two sub-packages inside `userservice/` are decoupled from each other at the import level. `handlers` defines the `Store` interface it requires; `store` provides the concrete type that satisfies it. Neither package imports the other. Only `main.go`, outside the `internal/` boundary, holds the concrete type reference and performs the wiring. This structure keeps each sub-package independently testable.\n","numLines":39,"startLine":1,"totalLines":39}}}
